# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baseball-reference
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baseball-reference/1888-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1888 throughout the world.
[src:baseball-reference/1901-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1901 throughout the world.
[src:baseball-reference/2021-seattle-mariners-season] The **2021 Seattle Mariners season** was the 45th season in franchise history.
[src:baseball-reference/2021-seattle-mariners-season] The Mariners played their 22nd full season (23rd overall) at T-Mobile Park, their home ballpark in Seattle, Washington.
[src:baseball-reference/2021-seattle-mariners-season] The M's entered this season with the longest active playoff drought in the four major North American professional sports leagues, attempting to make their first postseason in twenty years.
[src:baseball-reference/2021-seattle-mariners-season] Seattle is the only current Major League Baseball (MLB) franchise without a World Series appearance.
[src:baseball-reference/2021-seattle-mariners-season] This season was the second time during their drought that the Mariners won two more regular season games than the World Series champions.
[src:baseball-reference/2021-seattle-mariners-season] In the Mariners' 1–0 loss to the Los Angeles Dodgers on April 20, the two teams combined for three hits, tying the record for the fewest in an interleague game set by the Boston Red Sox and Montreal Expos in 1997.
[src:baseball-reference/2021-seattle-mariners-season] As that game featured a home run, a double, and a single, and the Mariners/Dodgers games featured just a double and two singles, it broke the record for fewest total bases in a regular-season interleague game.
[src:baseball-reference/2021-seattle-mariners-season] Pitcher Yusei Kikuchi was the team's lone MLB All-Star Game selection.
[src:baseball-reference/2021-seattle-mariners-season] On September 1, general manager Jerry Dipoto was promoted to president of baseball operations.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] In the past, practical applications have motivated the development of mathematical theories, which then became the subject of study in pure mathematics where abstract concepts are studied for their own sake.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] The activity of applied mathematics is thus intimately connected with research in pure mathematics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Historically, applied mathematics consisted principally of applied analysis, most notably differential equations; approximation theory (broadly construed, to include representations, asymptotic methods, variational methods, and numerical analysis); and applied probability.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] These areas of mathematics related directly to the development of Newtonian physics, and in fact, the distinction between mathematicians and physicists was not sharply drawn before the mid-19th century.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Engineering and computer science departments have traditionally made use of applied mathematics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Today, the term "applied mathematics" is used in a broader sense.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] It includes the classical areas noted above as well as other areas that have become increasingly important in applications.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Even fields such as number theory that are part of pure mathematics are now important in applications (such as cryptography), though they are not generally considered to be part of the field of applied mathematics *per se*.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] There is no consensus as to what the various branches of applied mathematics are.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Such categorizations are made difficult by the way mathematics and science change over time, and also by the way universities organize departments, courses, and degrees.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Many mathematicians distinguish between "applied mathematics", which is concerned with mathematical methods, and the "applications of mathematics" within science and engineering.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] A biologist using a population model and applying known mathematics would not be *doing* applied mathematics, but rather *using* it; however, mathematical biologists have posed problems that have stimulated the growth of pure mathematics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Mathematicians such as Poincaré and Arnold deny the existence of "applied mathematics" and claim that there are only "applications of mathematics." Similarly, non-mathematicians blend applied mathematics and applications of mathematics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] The use and development of mathematics to solve industrial problems is also called "industrial mathematics".
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] These are often considered interdisciplinary.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Sometimes, the term **applicable mathematics** is used to distinguish between the traditional applied mathematics that developed alongside physics and the many areas of mathematics that are applicable to real-world problems today, although there is no consensus as to a precise definition.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Mathematicians often distinguish between "applied mathematics" on the one hand, and the "applications of mathematics" or "applicable mathematics" both within and outside of science and engineering, on the other.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Some mathematicians emphasize the term applicable mathematics to separate or delineate the traditional applied areas from new applications arising from fields that were previously seen as pure mathematics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] For example, from this viewpoint, an ecologist or geographer using population models and applying known mathematics would not be doing applied, but rather applicable, mathematics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Other authors prefer describing *applicable mathematics* as a union of "new" mathematical applications with the traditional fields of applied mathematics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] With this outlook, the terms applied mathematics and applicable mathematics are thus interchangeable.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Historically, mathematics was most important in the natural sciences and engineering.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] However, since World War II, fields outside the physical sciences have spawned the creation of new areas of mathematics, such as game theory and social choice theory, which grew out of economic considerations.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Further, the utilization and development of mathematical methods expanded into other areas leading to the creation of new fields such as mathematical finance and data science.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Statistics is probably the most widespread mathematical science used in the social sciences.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Academic institutions are not consistent in the way they group and label courses, programs, and degrees in applied mathematics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] At some schools, there is a single mathematics department, whereas others have separate departments for Applied Mathematics and (Pure) Mathematics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] It is very common for Statistics departments to be separated at schools with graduate programs, but many undergraduate-only institutions include statistics under the mathematics department.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Many applied mathematics programs (as opposed to departments) consist primarily of cross-listed courses and jointly appointed faculty in departments representing applications.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Some Ph.D. programs in applied mathematics require little or no coursework outside mathematics, while others require substantial coursework in a specific area of application.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] In some respects this difference reflects the distinction between "application of mathematics" and "applied mathematics".
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Some universities in the U.K. host departments of *Applied Mathematics and Theoretical Physics*, but it is now much less common to have separate departments of pure and applied mathematics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] A notable exception to this is the Department of Applied Mathematics and Theoretical Physics at the University of Cambridge, housing the Lucasian Professor of Mathematics whose past holders include Isaac Newton, Charles Babbage, James Lighthill, Paul Dirac, and Stephen Hawking.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Schools with separate applied mathematics departments range from Brown University, which has a large Division of Applied Mathematics that offers degrees through the doctorate, to Santa Clara University, which offers only the M.S. in applied mathematics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Research universities dividing their mathematics department into pure and applied sections include MIT.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Students in this program also learn another skill (computer science, engineering, physics, pure math, etc.) to supplement their applied math skills.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Mathematics is used in all branches of engineering and has subsequently developed as distinct specialties within the engineering profession.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] For example, continuum mechanics is foundational to civil, Mechanical engineering and aerospace engineering, with courses in solid mechanics and fluid mechanics being important components of the engineering curriculum.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Continuum mechanics is also an important branch of mathematics in its own right.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] It has served as the inspiration for a vast range of difficult research questions for mathematicians involved in the analysis of partial differential equations, differential geometry and the calculus of variations.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Perhaps the most well-known mathematical problem posed by a continuum mechanical system is the question of Navier-Stokes existence and smoothness.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Prominent career mathematicians rather than engineers who have contributed to the mathematics of continuum mechanics are Clifford Truesdell, Walter Noll, Andrey Kolmogorov and George Batchelor.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] An essential discipline for many fields in engineering is that of control engineering.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] The associated mathematical theory of this specialism is control theory, a branch of applied mathematics that builds off the mathematics of dynamical systems.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Control theory has played a significant enabling role in modern technology, serving a foundational role in electrical, mechanical and aerospace engineering.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Like continuum mechanics, control theory has also become a field of mathematical research in its own right, with mathematicians such as Aleksandr Lyapunov, Norbert Wiener, Lev Pontryagin and Fields Medal recipient Pierre-Louis Lions contributing to its foundations.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Scientific computing includes applied mathematics (especially numerical analysis), computing science (especially high-performance computing), and mathematical modelling in a scientific discipline.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Computer science relies on logic, algebra, discrete mathematics such as graph theory, and combinatorics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Operations research and management science are often taught in faculties of engineering, business, and public policy.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Applied mathematics has substantial overlap with the discipline of statistics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Statistical theorists study and improve statistical procedures with mathematics, and statistical research often raises mathematical questions.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Statistical theory relies on probability and decision theory, and makes extensive use of scientific computing, analysis, and optimization; for the design of experiments, statisticians use algebra and combinatorial design.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Applied mathematicians and statisticians often work in a department of mathematical sciences (particularly at colleges and small universities).
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Actuarial science applies probability, statistics, and economic theory to assess risk in insurance, finance and other industries and professions.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Mathematical economics is the application of mathematical methods to represent theories and analyze problems in economics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] The applied methods usually refer to nontrivial mathematical techniques or approaches.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Mathematical economics is based on statistics, probability, mathematical programming (as well as other computational methods), operations research, game theory, and some methods from mathematical analysis.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] In this regard, it resembles (but is distinct from) financial mathematics, another part of applied mathematics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] with MSC2010 classifications for 'Game theory' at codes 91Axx Archived 2015-04-02 at the Wayback Machine and for 'Mathematical economics' at codes 91Bxx Archived 2015-04-02 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] The line between applied mathematics and specific areas of application is often blurred.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] Many universities teach mathematical and statistical courses outside the respective departments, in departments and areas including business, engineering, physics, chemistry, psychology, biology, computer science, scientific computation, information theory, and mathematical physics.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] The Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics is an international applied mathematics organization.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] As of 2024, the society has 14,000 individual members.
[src:baseball-reference/applied-math] The American Mathematics Society has its Applied Mathematics Group.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus has originated several popular new statistical tools that have become hallmarks of baseball analysis.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus is accredited by the Baseball Writers' Association of America.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Four of Baseball Prospectus's current regular writers are members of the Baseball Writers' Association of America and thus eligible to vote for nominees for Major League Baseball's post-season awards and the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus is formally an entity of Prospectus Entertainment Ventures, LLC, a private corporation that runs websites and publishes books focusing on the statistical analysis of the sports of baseball, basketball, and ice hockey.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] As of August 2014, the President & CEO is Joe Hamrahi, and Vice President is Dave Pease.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] For several years, Prospectus Entertainment Ventures (*PEV*) partnered with Football Outsiders for the publication and promotion of *Football Outsiders Almanac* (ISBN 1-4486-4845-9), before 2009 called *Pro Football Prospectus* (ISBN 0-452-28847-9).
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] On October 10, 2007, PEV launched *Basketball Prospectus,* a new website for the analysis of men's college and pro basketball, with Joe Sheehan taking the role of Managing Editor and announcing the lineup of principal writer-analysts for the site.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Initially, this website did not require a subscription for access, but it introduced subscriptions in 2011 for access to most of the material on the site.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] *BasketballProspectus.com*'s first annual book, *College Basketball Prospectus 2008–2009* (ISBN 0-452-28987-4), was published in October 2008.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] It released *Pro Basketball Prospectus 2009–10* for purchase online in October 2009.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Subsequently, it published both *College Basketball Prospectus 2010–11* (ISBN 1-4538-7282-5) and *Pro Basketball Prospectus 2010–11* (ISBN 1-4538-6899-2) in both print and online (PDF) modes.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] On March 19, 2008, Imagine Sports announced a strategic partnership with PEV and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Imagine sports owns the baseball simulation engine "Diamond Mind Baseball".
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] On October 14, 2008, PEV announced the acquisition of *Baseball Digest Daily* (BDD), an online blog devoted to baseball analysis and statistics.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Joe Hamrahi, new Chief Financial Officer of PEV and founder of BDD, reported that "PEV's decision to acquire Baseball Digest Daily further enhances the content offerings of Baseball Prospectus by adding some of the game's best analysts as well as over 100 pages of baseball news and original content.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] In addition, BDD's player tracker provides a platform for serious fans and fantasy baseball enthusiasts to easily monitor the progress of their teams, allowing users to manipulate and track the progress of an unlimited set of players over a customized period of time".
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] On February 23, 2009, Prospectus Entertainment Ventures (PEV) launched the website *Puck Prospectus* with the intent of providing cutting-edge analysis of hockey.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Will Carroll assumed the role of the Executive Editor, and Andrew Rothstein, the founder of *Puck Prospectus*, assumed the role of the Managing Editor.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Puck Prospectus published its first annual book, *Puck Prospectus 2010–2011* (ISBN 1-4538-1784-0) in both online and print formats.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Initially a free site, *Puck Prospectus* introduced subscriptions in 2011.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] On March 24, 2009, Baseball Prospectus announced that Nate Silver was stepping down as its Managing Partner, and Kevin Goldstein was assuming this role.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] At that time, PEV relinquished its previously announced financial interest in Silver's *FiveThirtyEight* blog.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] At the same time, it was announced that BP has a partnership relationship with ESPN.com.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] In January 2010, PEV's Managing Partner Kevin Goldstein reported that one of BP's founding members, Joe Sheehan, had departed the organization.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] He reported that John Perrotto had been elevated to full-time status on the BP staff and would become the new Editor-in-Chief of *BaseballProspectus.com*, taking over that responsibility from Christina Kahrl.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] And he reported that Jeff Euston was joining the BP staff and that Euston's *Cot's Baseball Contracts* website would be joining the Baseball Prospectus family.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] In February 2011, Perrotto was replaced as Editor-in-Chief by Steven Goldman.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] In February 2010, BP's "Fantasy Manager" Marc Normandin announced that BP had established a partnership with *Heater Magazine.* *Heater Magazine* ceased publication after the 2010 season.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] In November 2011, Kevin Goldstein announced that he was stepping down as PEV's Managing Partner in favor of Joe Hamrahi.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] On March 3, 2012, Hamrahi announced that Steven Goldman was stepping down as Editor-in-Chief of BaseballProspectus.com; Goldman had taken a position as a lead baseball writer for *Bleacher Report*.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Ben Lindbergh was named Managing Editor of Baseball Prospectus on March 5, 2012 and Editor-in-Chief of Baseball Prospectus on July 13, 2012.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] On April 30, 2012, PEV's Managing Partner Joe Hamrahi announced that "Dan Brooks, Harry Pavlidis, and Brooks Baseball have agreed to team up and join forces with Baseball Prospectus.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] BrooksBaseball.net is the premier site for PITCHf/x analysis and pitch classification".
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] On March 15, 2013, after explaining a week earlier that its key staff of writers had been hired away by ESPN, Baseball Prospectus's Dave Pease declared in response to a question in the comments: "Basketball Prospectus will not be publishing any new content.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] On March 8, Pease had written: "You've probably noticed our Basketball Prospectus Premium coverage has been pretty quiet lately.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] You may have also noticed that our core pro writers, Kevin Pelton, Bradford Doolittle, and John Gasaway are now writing for ESPN Insider on a regular basis.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Late last year, we learned that, following their completion of the Pro Basketball Prospectus 2012–13 and College Basketball Prospectus 2012–13 annuals, Kevin, Bradford, and John would be moving to ESPN on a full-time basis".
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus was founded in 1996 by Gary Huckabay, who recruited the initial contributor group of Clay Davenport, Rany Jazayerli, Christina Kahrl, and Joe Sheehan, with the publication of the first annual set of forecasts.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] "That first year, BP charged $20 for a statistics guide produced on a photocopier.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] It printed around 300 copies and sold about 170 to fellow statheads, even though the book was missing the St.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] 'It was terrible,' recalls Kahrl, 'but it nevertheless didn't discourage us.' Within a few years Brassey's Inc. published the guide, which grew to about 3,000 copies.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] The kind of sabermetric approach favored by Baseball Prospectus has gained significant acceptance by the management of many Major League Baseball clubs, notably the Boston Red Sox and Cleveland Indians.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] BP has often been considered the modern successor to Bill James' *Baseball Abstract* series of books in the 1980s.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Reflecting its legacy as a group of sabermetricians who met over the Internet, BP has no "main office." Working for BP is a second or part-time job for many of the regular staff, who conduct their work for BP in their own home offices.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] The website *BaseballProspectus.com* began in 1997 primarily as a way to present original sabermetric research; publish advanced baseball statistics such as EqA, the Davenport Translations (DT's), and VORP; and promote sales of the annual book.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Beginning in 2003, the site placed most of its new articles, its PECOTA forecasts, and some of its statistical databases in a "premium" section that could be accessed only by subscription.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] However, in May 2011, BP "announced it has made its entire archive of premium and fantasy content over one year old completely and permanently free to the public".
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Until 2007, when the site began to post general advertising, the premium subscriptions and book sales were Baseball Prospectus' main source of revenues.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus does not publish a financial report or information about its subscriber base, but it appears to have used its income to expand its breadth of coverage, and it has not increased its subscription prices since initiating its premium service.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] It also offers a subscription to those interested in fantasy baseball, at a lower price than the premium subscriptions and giving access to fewer features and articles.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Given the competing career opportunities for some of BP's best-known and most statistics-savvy analysts, maintaining a fresh supply of sabermetrically sophisticated writers remains a challenge.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] At least three new regular BP writers (winner Ken Funck, Tim Kniker, and Matt Swartz) were discovered through this *Prospectus Idol* contest.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] In addition, BP had added Eric Seidman to its staff early in 2009 and then acquired Russell Carleton ("Pizza Cutter") and Colin Wyers in December 2009 to bolster its coverage of technical sabermetric issues.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] As late as the Fall of 2008, Seidman, Swartz, Carleton, Wyers, Daniel Novick and BP Idol finalist Brian Cartwright made up the entire staff of "Statistically Speaking" aka StatSpeak at MVN.com.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Carleton left the BP staff in May 2010, but returned in July 2012.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Seidman and Swartz left in February 2011.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Wyers was hired away by the Houston Astros in October 2013.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] In the press release announcing his hire, Jeff Luhnow noted, "Colin Wyers is a brilliant man with lots of well thought-out, practical, ideas.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] He is insuring the financial security of this company for years to come.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Oh yes, and his personal hygiene is above reproach".
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] So teams court them as part of their effort to win games".
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] By the beginning of the 2011 baseball season, none of BP's founders was an active contributor to the website or publications, though some of their earlier articles were included in two *Best of Baseball Prospectus* compendia that were published in 2011.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus writers promote several theories on proper baseball management and analysis, many of which are contrary to those of conventional baseball wisdom.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus researchers have concluded that there is no repeatable ability of clutch hitting.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] In an article published in 2006, Nate Silver argued that clutch hitting ability does exist to a degree.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] He argued that although not as important as traditional baseball analysis would suggest, clutch hitting ability was more significant than other sabermetric studies had shown.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] The article also found there to be a connection between clutch hitting ability and situational hitting, or the ability to adjust a hitting approach to fit the given situation.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus writers often successfully argue that traditional baseball statistics such as RBIs, wins, and batting average are poor reflections of a player's true contributions.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] For example, they have argued that RBIs are too dependent on factors outside of the player's control, namely the production of other hitters in the lineup.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] They similarly argue that wins are too affected by factors such as the team's offense and bullpen.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus writers assert that teams are typically inefficient in their use of their best relievers.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Teams typically assign their most effective reliever to the position of closer, using him in only save situations.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] According to many Baseball Prospectus writers, a team's best reliever should be used when the opposing team has its best chance at increasing its chances of winning.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Many writers argue that the sacrifice bunt and stolen base are overused in baseball.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Teams will often attempt these plays when the score is close.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Writers for Baseball Prospectus often argue that teams are, on average, actually lowering their expected number of runs scored.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] They argue that stolen base attempts are not completed frequently enough for them to be beneficial to the offense.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] For sacrifice bunts, they argue that the team is giving up more by sacrificing an out than they gain by advancing a runner one base.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Their thinking is derived from the grid of expected runs in an inning based on the outs and runner situation, which shows that the sacrifice is detrimental to a team given average players in most of the situations in which it is typically used.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] In a series of articles in 2004, James Click argued that sacrifice bunts are beneficial in some situations, dependent on the quality of the batter at the plate and the situation in the game.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus writers use a wide variety of sabermetric tools.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Voros McCracken's pathbreaking article on Defense Independent Pitching Statistics also first appeared on the BP website.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus, as well as other sabermetric analysts, are criticized for taking the human aspect out of the game of baseball.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Nate Silver, BP's Managing Partner at the time, responded to this criticism in "An Open Letter to Murray Chass," including offering to meet Chass to watch a ballgame.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Silver expounded on the case for a positive impact of sabermetrics on the game of baseball in an article "How Sabermetrics Helps Build a Better Ballgame," published on *Baseball Analysts.com*.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Another type of criticism comes from those who believe that by broadening its coverage and audience, Baseball Prospectus is becoming more like the mainstream media and losing what made it unique.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus was widely criticized for publishing and aggressively promoting a 2003 story claiming that banished player/manager Pete Rose had reached an agreement to return to baseball.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Will Carroll made the rounds on television and radio, claiming to have spoken to unnamed sources who had actually seen the agreement.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] Spokesmen for both Rose and Major League Baseball refuted the claim, but Carroll and his colleagues insisted their reporting was accurate.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] No other news source confirmed the story.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-prospectus] In fact, Rose was not reinstated and remains banned from baseball.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] Founder Sean Forman began developing the website while working on his Ph.D. dissertation in applied math and computational science at the University of Iowa.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] While writing his dissertation, he had also been writing articles on and blogging about sabermetrics.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] Forman's database was originally built from the *Total Baseball* series of baseball encyclopedias.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] The website went online in April 2000, after first being launched in February 2000 as part of the website for the *Big Bad Baseball Annual*.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] It was originally built as a web interface to the Lahman Baseball Database, though it now employs a variety of data sources.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] In 2004, Forman founded Sports Reference.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] Sports Reference is a website that came out of the Baseball Reference website.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] The company was incorporated as Sports Reference, LLC in 2007.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] In 2006, Forman left his job as a math professor at Saint Joseph's University to focus on Baseball Reference full-time.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] In February 2009, Fantasy Sports Ventures took a minority stake in Sports Reference, for a "low seven-figure sum".
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] In late April 2021, the site changed a number of identifying names, "discontinuing the use of nicknames that are racially or ethnically influenced" and "names based upon a player's disability", such as Chief Bender and Dummy Hoy, who are now listed as Charles Bender and Billy Hoy, respectively.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] To compare ballplayers to one-another it offers "Black Ink" and "Gray Ink" tests, which tally a player's dominance and overall productivity against his peers.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] In 2012, it began to offer Jay Jaffe's Jaffe Wins Above Replacement Score (JAWS) statistic for comparing players of different eras against each other by weighing their performance in the prime as well as their entire career.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference began including its version of Wins Above Replacement (WAR) in 2010.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] Its version determining a player's value differs slightly from other baseball statistics websites, including FanGraphs and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference has its own baseball encyclopedia, a wiki called "Baseball Reference Bullpen", which can be edited by anyone and is modeled after Wikipedia.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-reference] As of November 2025, the Bullpen contains more than 123,000 articles.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] Because the flow of a baseball game has natural breaks, and player performance is individually measurable, the sport lends itself to easy record-keeping and compiling statistics.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] Since the National League (NL) was founded in 1876, statistics in the most elite levels of professional baseball have been kept, with efforts to standardize the stats and their compilation improving during the early 20th century.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] Such efforts have evolved together with advances in technology ever since.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] The NL was joined by the American League (AL) in 1903; together the two constitute modern Major League Baseball.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] A number of statistics are defined in the *Official Baseball Rules*, which task the official scorer with providing a report after each game.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] Advances in both statistical analysis and technology made possible by the "PC revolution" of the 1980s and 1990s have driven teams and fans to evaluate players by an ever more elaborate set of statistics, which hold them to ever-evolving standards.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] With the advent of these methods, players can be compared across different eras and run scoring environments.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] The practice of keeping records of player achievements was started in the 19th century by English-American sportswriter Henry Chadwick.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] Based on his experience with the sport of cricket, Chadwick devised the predecessors to modern-day statistics including batting average, runs scored, and runs allowed.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] However, the recent advent of sabermetrics has created statistics drawing from a greater breadth of player performance measures and playing field variables.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] Sabermetrics and comparative statistics attempt to provide an improved measure of a player's performance and contributions to his team from year to year, frequently against a statistical performance average.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] Comprehensive, historical baseball statistics were difficult for the average fan to access until 1951, when researcher Hy Turkin published *The Complete Encyclopedia of Baseball*.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] In 1969, Macmillan Publishing printed its first *Baseball Encyclopedia*, using a computer to compile statistics for the first time.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] Known as "Big Mac", the encyclopedia became the standard baseball reference until 1988, when *Total Baseball* was released by Warner Books using more sophisticated technology.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] The publication of *Total Baseball* led to the discovery of several "phantom ballplayers", such as Lou Proctor, who did not belong in official record books and were removed.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] Throughout modern baseball, a few core statistics have been traditionally referenced – batting average, RBI, and home runs.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] To this day, a player who leads the league in all of these three statistics earns the "Triple Crown".
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] For pitchers, wins, ERA, and strikeouts are the most often-cited statistics, and a pitcher leading his league in these statistics may also be referred to as a "triple crown" winner.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] General managers and baseball scouts have long used the major statistics, among other factors and opinions, to understand player value.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] Managers, catchers and pitchers use the statistics of batters of opposing teams to develop pitching strategies and set defensive positioning on the field.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] Managers and batters study opposing pitcher performance and motions in attempting to improve hitting.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] Scouts use stats when they are looking at a player who they may end up drafting or signing to a contract.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] Some sabermetric statistics have entered the mainstream baseball world that measure a batter's overall performance including on-base plus slugging, commonly referred to as OPS.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] OPS adds the hitter's on-base percentage (number of times reached base by any means divided by total plate appearances) to their slugging percentage (total bases divided by at-bats).
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] Some argue that the OPS formula is flawed and that more weight should be shifted towards OBP (on-base percentage).
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] The statistic wOBA (weighted on-base average) attempts to correct for this.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] OPS is also useful when determining a pitcher's level of success.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] "Opponent on-base plus slugging" (OOPS) is becoming a popular tool to evaluate a pitcher's actual performance.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] When analyzing a pitcher's statistics, some useful categories include K/9IP (strikeouts per nine innings), K/BB (strikeouts per walk), HR/9 (home runs per nine innings), WHIP (walks plus hits per inning pitched), and OOPS (opponent on-base plus slugging).
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] However, since 2001, more emphasis has been placed on defense-independent pitching statistics, including defense-independent ERA (dERA), in an attempt to evaluate a pitcher's performance regardless of the strength of the defensive players behind them.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] All of the above statistics may be used in certain game situations.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] For example, a certain hitter's ability to hit left-handed pitchers might incline a manager to increase their opportunities to face left-handed pitchers.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] Other hitters may have a history of success against a given pitcher (or vice versa), and the manager may use this information to create a favorable match-up.
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] This is often referred to as "playing the percentages".
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] The following listings include abbreviations and/or acronyms for both historic baseball statistics and those based on modern mathematical formulas known popularly as "metrics".
[src:baseball-reference/baseball-statistics] The explanations below are for quick reference and do not fully or completely define the statistic; for the strict definition, see the linked article for each statistic.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] Since 2009, the magazine has been owned by Bloomberg L.P. and became a monthly in June 2024.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] Originally published as a resource for business managers, the magazine shifted its strategy in the 1970s and added consumers outside the business world.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] By 1975, the magazine was carrying more advertising pages annually than any other magazine in the United States.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] Shepard served as editor-in-chief from 1984 until 2005, when he was chosen to be the founding dean of the CUNY Graduate School of Journalism.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] Under Shepard, *Businessweek*'s readership grew to more than six million in the late 1980s.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] In late 2009, Bloomberg L.P. bought the magazine—reportedly for between $2 million to $5 million plus assumption of liabilities—and renamed it *Bloomberg BusinessWeek*.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] News reports published in 2019 suggest McGraw-Hill received the high end of the speculated price, at $5 million, along with the assumption of debt.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] In early 2010, the magazine title was restyled as *Bloomberg Businessweek* (with a lowercase "w") as part of a redesign.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] During the following years, the bold, eclectic, playful, and memetic face of *Businessweek* was cultivated largely by *Businessweek*'s creative director Richard Turley, then Rob Vargas (from 2014), and Deputy Creative director Tracy Ma (from 2011 through 2016).
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] During her time at *Businessweek*, Ma worked on over 200 issues.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] As of 2014, the magazine was losing $30 million per year, about half of the $60 million it was reported losing in 2009.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] Adler resigned as editor-in-chief and was replaced by Josh Tyrangiel, who had been deputy managing editor of *Time* magazine.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] In 2016, Bloomberg announced changes to *Businessweek*, which was losing between $20 and $30 million.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] Nearly 30 Bloomberg News journalists were let go across the U.S., Europe, and Asia, and it was announced that a new version of *Bloomberg Businessweek* would launch the following year.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] In addition, editor-in-chief Ellen Pollock stepped down from her position, and Washington Bureau Chief Megan Murphy was named editor-in-chief.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] Megan Murphy served as editor from November 2016; until she stepped down from the role in January 2018, and Joel Weber was appointed by the editorial board in her place.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] Brad Stone was appointed editor of the magazine in January 2024, when the magazine switched to publishing biweekly.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] In June of the same year, the magazine became a monthly.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] On October 4, 2018, *Bloomberg Businessweek* published "The Big Hack: How China Used a Tiny Chip to Infiltrate U.S.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] Companies," an article by Jordan Robertson and Michael Riley that claimed that China had hacked dozens of technology corporations, including Amazon and Apple, by placing an extra integrated circuit on a Supermicro server motherboard during manufacturing.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] Pingwest, a media company founded in Silicon Valley and based in Beijing, identified the chip mentioned in the article as a balun.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] The company pointed out that its size made it impossible to implement any form of attack; it did not have the storage space required to store commands that would allow a hacker to infiltrate the hardware.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] They suggested that *Businessweek* had underestimated security standards employed by Amazon and Apple.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] Bloomberg's claims have faced significant scrutiny.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] By 2 p.m. on the day of publication, Apple, Amazon, and Supermicro issued blanket denials, which Bloomberg reported.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] Within the week, the United States Department of Homeland Security stated that it saw no reason to question those refutations.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] The National Security Agency, as well as the Government Communications Headquarters and National Cyber Security Centre of the United Kingdom, also denied the article's claims.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] In 2021, Bloomberg published a follow-up article that stood by its allegations.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] International editions of *Businessweek* were available on newsstands in Europe and Asia until 2005, when publication of regional editions was suspended to help increase foreign readership of customized European and Asian versions of *Businessweek*'s website.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] That same year, however, the Russian edition was launched in collaboration with Rodionov Publishing House.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] At the same time, *Businessweek* partnered with InfoPro Management, a publishing and market research company based in Beirut, Lebanon, to produce the Arabic version of the magazine in 22 Arab countries.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] In 2011, *Bloomberg Businessweek* continued its international expansion and announced plans to introduce a Polish-language edition called *Bloomberg Businessweek Polska*, as well as a Chinese edition, which was relaunched in November 2011.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] Also in 2011, *Bloomberg Businessweek* launched an iPad version of the magazine using Apple's subscription billing service.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] The iPad edition was the first to use this subscription method, which allows one to subscribe via an iTunes account.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] There are over 100,000 subscribers to the iPad edition of *Businessweek*.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] In 2011, *Adweek* named *Bloomberg Businessweek* as the top business magazine in the U.S.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] In 2012, *Bloomberg Businessweek* won the general excellence award for general-interest magazines at the National Magazine Awards.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] Also in 2012, *Bloomberg Businessweek* editor Josh Tyrangiel was named magazine editor of the year by *Ad Age*.
[src:baseball-reference/bloomberg-businessweek] In 2014, *Bloomberg Businessweek* won a Society of American Business Editors and Writers Best in Business award for magazines, general excellence.
